00:33:09.440 --> 00:33:10.540
enter the data manually?

00:33:10.540 --> 00:33:13.840
Or take a photo of
their cards?

00:33:13.840 --> 00:33:15.340
You know, OCR it?

00:33:15.340 --> 00:33:18.200
Is that something users
don't want to do?

00:33:18.200 --> 00:33:19.760
PETER HAZLEHURST: We find
a couple of issues.

00:33:19.760 --> 00:33:22.500
One is it's just a pain.

00:33:22.500 --> 00:33:24.780
So it's an effort to do it.

00:33:24.780 --> 00:33:27.880
And discovering Google Wallet
as an endpoint to do that,

00:33:27.880 --> 00:33:30.980
rather than being able to be in
online banking and getting

00:33:30.980 --> 00:33:33.220
a notification that you can
now push your cards into

00:33:33.220 --> 00:33:36.020
Google Wallet, actually creates
another channel for

00:33:36.020 --> 00:33:39.240
people to be aware that Google
Wallet even exists.

00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:40.650
And we focused in
on simplicity.

00:33:40.650 --> 00:33:41.890
Making it really, really easy.

00:33:41.890 --> 00:33:45.250
All you have to do is trust your
bank, which you generally

00:33:45.250 --> 00:33:47.330
do, to Google.

00:33:47.330 --> 00:33:49.770
And then you're going to be
able to push information.

00:33:49.770 --> 00:33:51.300
And the upshot of that
is that the banks

00:33:51.300 --> 00:33:52.510
could also push changes.

00:33:52.510 --> 00:33:56.120
So if, for example, your card
expires, or it runs out, or

00:33:56.120 --> 00:33:58.680
you get a new card issued they
can push the changes, as well,

00:33:58.680 --> 00:34:00.540
without you having to
be involved anymore.

00:34:00.540 --> 00:34:02.080
And that's a huge advantage
to consumers.

00:34:02.080 --> 00:34:05.120
Because we see a lot of people
with cards in their Wallet

00:34:05.120 --> 00:34:06.720
that expire over time.

00:34:06.720 --> 00:34:08.670
And then when they're about to
make a payment, they're like,

00:34:08.670 --> 00:34:11.020
Ugh, OK I have to go and update
it and make a change

00:34:11.020 --> 00:34:12.060
and things like that.

00:34:12.060 --> 00:34:14.860
And this keeps the issuer
in with a channel

00:34:14.860 --> 00:34:17.514
to communicate back.

00:34:17.514 --> 00:34:18.900
Cool.

00:34:18.900 --> 00:34:23.940
AUDIENCE: Like somebody asked,
the coupons are only for

00:34:23.940 --> 00:34:24.440
offline use.

00:34:24.440 --> 00:34:27.650
Are there any plans to make them
available for online use,

00:34:27.650 --> 00:34:30.320
like you get a coupon on a
website and use it on another

00:34:30.320 --> 00:34:32.190
website, for instance.

00:34:32.190 --> 00:34:32.560
PETER HAZLEHURST: Yeah.

00:34:32.560 --> 00:34:34.949
So we haven't announced anything
in the area around

00:34:34.949 --> 00:34:36.520
what we're doing on the
online side of things.

00:34:36.520 --> 00:34:39.699
But it's a key area of focus for
us, to make sure that the

00:34:39.699 --> 00:34:42.260
coupons and the offers that you
save are available for use

00:34:42.260 --> 00:34:42.960
everywhere.

00:34:42.960 --> 00:34:43.310
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:34:43.310 --> 00:34:46.070
Thanks.

00:34:46.070 --> 00:34:48.580
AUDIENCE: You mentioned and
demonstrated the creation of a

00:34:48.580 --> 00:34:50.600
coupon on the web page.

00:34:50.600 --> 00:34:53.900
Would you mind going into more
detail about how the

00:34:53.900 --> 00:34:54.610
redemption works?

00:34:54.610 --> 00:34:55.929
The recognition of coupons?

00:34:55.929 --> 00:34:57.880
So, say I'm a retailer,
I have a coupon.

00:34:57.880 --> 00:35:01.150
How do I know that that user has
my coupon in their Wallet?

00:35:01.150 --> 00:35:03.800
Can I look for other coupons
from competitors in their

00:35:03.800 --> 00:35:05.930
Wallet when they scan
their phone?

00:35:05.930 --> 00:35:07.480
How does that work?

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:08.970
PETER HAZLEHURST: So it's
actually pretty simple in

00:35:08.970 --> 00:35:10.120
terms of the redemption path.

00:35:10.120 --> 00:35:14.880
So either because of tapping,
we're going to push the coupon

00:35:14.880 --> 00:35:18.700
information through Mifare
into the NFC terminal.

00:35:18.700 --> 00:35:21.690
Or if it's a show-and-scan
type of thing, then the

00:35:21.690 --> 00:35:24.500
cashier is going to physically
take an image of a bar code or

00:35:24.500 --> 00:35:25.630
type in the card number.

00:35:25.630 --> 00:35:28.325
So at that point, you as the
retailer know this transaction

00:35:28.325 --> 00:35:29.410
has come through.

00:35:29.410 --> 00:35:31.850
Right now, we haven't made it
possible for a retailer to

00:35:31.850 --> 00:35:33.460
look at what else is stored
in the Wallet.

00:35:33.460 --> 00:35:36.530
AUDIENCE: So but when I tap that
NFC, do I have the coupon

00:35:36.530 --> 00:35:37.540
open on my phone already?

00:35:37.540 --> 00:35:39.610
Or does it just look at my
coupons and go, Oh, that's

00:35:39.610 --> 00:35:43.060
valid, I'll redeem
that for you.

00:35:43.060 --> 00:35:44.520
PETER HAZLEHURST: So let me make
sure-- can you ask the

00:35:44.520 --> 00:35:44.985
question again?

00:35:44.985 --> 00:35:45.130
Sorry.

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:47.390
AUDIENCE: So I show up at
a store with my phone.

00:35:47.390 --> 00:35:48.990
And I want to redeem a coupon.

00:35:48.990 --> 00:35:51.780
So when I get to the check-out
I'll just tap in on the NFC.

00:35:51.780 --> 00:35:54.010
Do I have to select the coupon
I want to use first?

00:35:54.010 --> 00:35:57.780
Or does it figure out, based
on what's in my wallet, Oh,

00:35:57.780 --> 00:35:58.770
you're at Walgreen's, here.

00:35:58.770 --> 00:36:01.350
Here's this Walgreen's coupon
that you saved previously,

00:36:01.350 --> 00:36:02.650
I'll use that.

00:36:02.650 --> 00:36:03.500
PETER HAZLEHURST: So basically,
what you're going

00:36:03.500 --> 00:36:06.090
to want to do is choose the one
that you want to be active

00:36:06.090 --> 00:36:06.930
at that point in time.

00:36:06.930 --> 00:36:08.475
And then it's going
to passed through.

00:36:08.475 --> 00:36:08.810
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:36:08.810 --> 00:36:09.280
Cool.

00:36:09.280 --> 00:36:09.610
PETER HAZLEHURST: OK?

00:36:09.610 --> 00:36:12.530
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:36:12.530 --> 00:36:13.250
PETER HAZLEHURST: OK.

